rk ethic among the customers and factories we work with on a daily basis.  This workforce has always been ready to work!”\r\n\r\nThese Southern states tout business attractive attributes such as low taxation, favorable environmental and regulatory laws, positive workforce factors, and living environment.  According to the article in Chief Executive magazine, one CEO responded, “Do not overtax business.  Make sure your tax scheme does not drive business to another state.  Have a regulatory environment and regulators that encourage good business – not one that punishes businesses for minor infractions.  Good employment laws help too.  Let companies decide what benefits and terms will attract and keep the quality of employee they need.  Rules that make it hard, if not impossible, to separate from a non-productive employee make companies fearful to hire or locate in a state.”\r\n\r\nIt seems that state sponsored incentives are not enough for a state to achieve high rankings.  Business leaders emphasized the criticality of consistency in policies and state regulations that enable them to generate long term forecasts and anticipate growth potential.  Evaluation of a state’s overall attitude toward the business community and the work ethic and aptitudes of a state’s population were also cited as major determinants in the decision making process for a business considering relocation and/or expansion into a state.\r\n\r\nFor example, Texas has been a strong #1 contender since 2005, creating more jobs in 2010 – about 250,000 – than any other state.  They also offer the second-lowest taxes in the nation and a diverse, highly flexible labor market.  Although improvements are always needed in any state, clearly these states are on the right road to recovery and job growth.\r\n\r\nTopics of paramount concern among the CEO’s remain job killing legislation and the demonization of the business community.  Corporate hallways reverberate with the message of one CEO respondent who was 