id then normal concrete hence it continuously needs to  be mixed so that it gives the desired effect needed for its industrial  uses.\r\nRCC should be such that the roller does not sink and it allows enough  distribution of the binder during the process of mixing and compacting.  Basically it shouldn’t be too dry and neither too wet, it should be  somewhere in the middle to be used at its best.\r\nThe placement of RCC is similar to pavement. It is placed by dump trucks  or conveyors and then they are spread by the help of bulldozers across  the pathway. After the entire process is complete it is then compacted  by the vibratory rollers.\r\nEver since RCC came into existence, it has been used for concrete  pavement. But since a couple of years its purpose has been extended and  has increasingly been used for making dams. The reason is that the RCC  has a low content of cement in its mixture then the conventional  concrete and hence it leads to less heat generation while currying.\r\n\r\nTwo major applications of RCC:\r\nConstruction of Dams\r\nEver since Roller Compacted Concrete has replaced the conventional  concrete in dam building, the construction can now be completed in much  shorter time, around 1 to 2 years and can easily make use of a greater  volume of the concrete in one day, up to 18000 cubic meters as compared  to the normal concrete.\r\nWith RCC segments of a dam are built in succeeding horizontal layers,  lift by lift which results in a downstream slope and looks like a  concrete staircase. When the first layer is placed, it provides support  to the earth moving equipment and hence making the placement of other  layer one after the other much simpler. After the deposition of RCC  takes place in the first layer, dozers are used to spread them making it  wide enough to become 1 foot thick. The process is then continued with  other deposits.\r\nThe first dam that was built in USA with the Roller Compacted Concrete  was named the Willow Creek Dam. It was constructed by the army corps of  Engineers during November 1981 to February 1983 in the Columbia River.  Construction took place in a lesser time then expected as well as a  lesser budget then had been estimated (expected was $50 million while  actual was $35 million).\r\nRoad Construction\r\nRoad construction follows the similar process as in the construction of  dam by first putting layers of the concrete successively through either  dump trucks or conveyors and then spreading it through either bulldozers  or modified Asphalt pavers. One important object used in the  construction of road includes extenders whose job is to reduce the costs  as well as increase the temperature when the cement hydration is taking  place. Fractioning of RCC is done by using two methods which include,  Soil Compaction Principle and Basic Concrete Technology.\r\nCanada and Spain are two places where the usage of RCC for concrete  pavement has been widespread and is seen to be increasing day after day.\r\nRCC hence has been very beneficial when it comes to construction of  infrastructure. It not only allows the completion of project in a  smaller period of time but also at a smaller cost and a better quality.','Roller Compacted Concrete','','inherit','open','open','','68-revision-2','','','2011-05-16 21:45:24','2011-05-16 21:45:24','',68,'http://www.gulfatlanticequipment.com/blog/68-revision-2',0,'revision','',0),(183,1,'2011-06-03 19:45:20','2011-06-03 19:45:20','Roller-Compacted Concrete (RCC) or rolled concrete is a special blend of concrete that has the same ingredients as conventional concrete but in different ratios. It has cement, water, and aggregates, but RCC is much drier and essentially has no slump. RCC is placed in a manner similar to paving, often by dump trucks or conveyors, spread by bulldozers or special modified asphalt pavers. After placement it is compacted by vibratory rollers.\r\nRCC is typically used for concrete pavement, but it is increasingly used to build concrete dams because the low cement content causes less heat to be generated while curing than do conventional massive concrete pours.\r\nFor dam applications, RCC sections are built lift-by-lift in successive horizontal layers resulting in a downstream slope that resembles a concrete staircase. Once a layer is placed, it can immediately support the earth-moving equipment to place the next layer. After RCC is deposited on the lift surface, small dozers typically spread it in one-foot-thick layers (300mm).[2]\r\nRCC, a durable paving material that carries heavy loads, is now developing as a fast, economical construction method for dams, off-highway pavement projects, heavy-duty parking and storage areas, and as a base for conventional pavement. RCC is a stiff, zero-slump concrete mixture with the consistency of damp gravel comprised of local aggregates or crushed recycled concrete, Portland cement, and water. The mixture is placed and roller compacted with the same commonly available equipment used for asphalt pavement construction. The process requires no forms, finishing, surface texturing, or joint sawing and sealing.\r\nBecause of its low water-cement ratio, RCC typically has high strengths similar to, or even greater than, conventional concrete. RCC\'s high-strength properties combined with ease of construction and high rate of production often make RCC more economical than a flexible pavement. Additionally, more than 20 years of exposure as logging roads in cold climates have demonstrated that RCC has adequate resistance to freezing and thawing.\r\nRCC got its start in the Seventies, when the Canadian logging industry switched to environmentally cleaner, land-based log-sorting methods. The industry needed a strong pavement to stand up to massive loads and specialized equipment. Yet economy was equally important: log-sorting yards can span 40 acres or more. RCC met this challenge and has since expanded to other heavy-duty applications.\r\nToday, RCC is used when strength, durability, and economy are primary needs:\r\nPort, intermodal, and military facilities; parking, storage, and staging areas;\r\nstreets, intersections, and low-speed roads.\r\nRCC\'s economy of scale made it ideal for roads, parking, and staging areas at the Honda Plant in Lincoln, Alabama. At 140 acres, it\'s the largest RCC pavement project to date.\r\nRCC owes much of its economy to high-volume, high-speed construction methods. Large-capacity mixers set the pace. Normally, RCC is blended in continuous-mixing pugmills at or near the construction site. These high-output pugmills have the mixing efficiency needed to evenly disperse the relatively small amount of water used.\r\nDump trucks transport the RCC and discharge it into an asphalt paver, which places the material in layers up to 10 inches thick and 42 feet wide.\r\nNo rutting, no pot holes, the high strength of RCC pavements eliminates common and costly problems traditionally associated with asphalt pavements. RCC pavements not only resist rutting they span soft localized sub-grades, will not deform under heavy, concentrated loads, do not deteriorate from spills of fuels and hydraulic fluids and will not soften under high temperatures.','Roller Compacted Concrete','','inherit','open','open','','68-revision-3','','','2011-06-03 19:45:20','2011-06-03 19:45:20','',68,'http://www.gulfatlanticequipment.com/blog/68-revision-3',0,'revision','',0),(253,1,'2011-06-08 20:05:14','2011-06-08 20:05:14','<h1>MOBILE BATCH PLANTS</h1>\r\nWith the introduction of mobile batch plants as a response to burgeoning demand for concrete due to an increase in construction, concrete producers continuously responded with innovative solutions to cater to the requirements of clients. Any small difference in the quality of material supplied or any delays in transportation could be very costly for both client and producer. However, with the advent of <strong>mobile batch plants</strong> or mobile batching plants, there has been a great increase in the quality of concrete supplied and delivery times have also been reduced significantly.  In addition, the mobile batch plant allows the producer to move quickly and efficiently around a large site or transport the entire operation to a new site in a matter of hours in many cases.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignright size-full wp-image-148\" title=\"mobile-batch-plants\" src=\"http://www.gulfatlanticequipment.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/mobile-batch-plants.jpg\" alt=\"mobile batch plants\" width=\"320\" height=\"150\" />\r\n<h2>What are mobile batch plants?</h2>\r\nUnlike conventional batching plants mobile plants can be transported from site to site with minimal set-up time. Earlier, engineers made use of mobile placing booms as well as truck-mounted concrete pumps. Apart from this they had no other option to get concrete on site. The most commonly used method was using plants in the city for mixing and then transporting the concrete onto the construction site via mixer trucks.\r\n<h3>Advantage of mobile batch plants</h3>\r\nHowever, since concrete is sensitive to time and heat, spending too much time on the road results in a significant loss of quality.\r\n\r\nThey are reliable due to the high level of technology involved in producing them and provide accurate results. Mobile batching plants can work in a wide range of environmental conditions and give their maximum potential.\r\n\r\nAnother benefit of mobile batching plants is that they can be quickly adjusted according to the requirements of the job. Since the batching is done at the construction site itself, the adjustments can be done swiftly in a matter of seconds by adjusting the plant or mix design.\r\n\r\nCompanies need a highly functional mobile batch plant so that the processes can be completed to the best standards. Even a  minor failure to detect the requirements properly can cost a company  immensely. A quality mobile concrete batch plant is the base to build your a highly mobile workforce for any producer.\r\n\r\nIf you are thinking that selecting a mobile concrete batch plant is a very easy  task then let me tell you that the decision relating to the upgrading,  replacing or buying of a new mobile concrete plant is indeed a very challenging  task. In fact even the senior most batch plant operators can be seen  baffled when decision related to batching plants needs to be taken. It would be beneficial to consult a highly experienced equipment dealer like Gulf Atlantic Industrial Equipment, Inc. before making such a critical investment.\r\n\r\nOverall, <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">mobile batching plants</span> have been a welcome addition to the line of batching plants available as they have low operational costs and can be quickly adjusted according to <a style=\"text-decoration: none; color: black;\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Construction\">construction</a> site requirements.\r\n\r\nRelated articles:<a href=\"http://www.gulfatlanticequipment.com/products-portable-concrete-batch-plants.php\"></a>\r\n\r\n<address><a href=\"http://www.gulfatlanticequipment.com/products-portable-concrete-batch-plants.php\">portable concrete batch plants </a>\r\n</address> <address>concrete batch plants</address> <address>batch plant mixer</address> <address>pug mills\r\n</address>','Mobile Batch Plants','','inherit','open','open','','5-revision-17','','','2011-06-08 20:05:14','2011-06-08 20:05:14','',5,'http://www.gulfatlanticequipment.com/blog/5-revision-17',0,'revision','',0),(231,1,'2011-06-13 19:53:02','2011-06-13 19:53:02','A batch plant mixer is usually used when it comes to using ready-mixed  concrete. This is because it saves a lot of time and is ideal with large  projects. It originated from the 1940s, when the world was trying to  build back after the war, and is still popular in many building projects  now. The batch plant mixer is perfect to be used in small spaces and for larger commercial projects. R&amp;S Industries manufacturers precision engineered Central Tilt  Batch Plant Mixers are manufactured in capacities of 10, 12, 15, and 18 cubic yards.\r\n\r\nBy using a batch plant mixer, the means that the concrete will then  need to be moved to a truck mixer to be able to deliver the product to the job site.\r\n\r\n•    Ready-mix concrete can be mixed in a variety of ways. Concrete  can be mixed with the truck mixers, and this type of concrete is called  truck-mixed, or transit-mixed, concrete.  Ready-mix concrete can also be  mixed in a plant mixer, then moved to the drum of the truck mixer.  These central mixing plants use a stationary mixer to partially mix the  concrete. This type of concrete is called shrink-mixed concrete, since  it reduces the volume of the concrete. The final type of concrete mixing  used is called central mixing, or wet batch, concrete. Central mixing  is cost-effective since it requires less wear on the truck drums.  However, some plant mixers may require more maintenance, but they  produce higher quality concrete due to the superior mixing.\r\n\r\nFunction\r\n•    Ready-mix concrete is usually delivered by trucks with rotating  drum mixers. Drum mixer trucks are designed with a pair of blades that  spin one way to mix the concrete, and then can spin the opposite  direction to release the mixture. Although most concrete mixer trucks  discharge concrete from the back, newer trucks feature front-discharge  chutes. These front-discharge trucks require less maneuvering to place  the concrete in the correct location.\r\nTypes\r\n•    Types of plant mixers include: tilt drum mixer, horizontal shaft  mixers, pan mixers and slurry mixers. Tilt drum mixers are the most  common and are known for their efficiency. Horizontal shaft mixers are  good for producing higher-quality concrete products because of their  powerful blending capabilities.  Pan mixers are used for pre-cast concrete operations.\r\nBenefits\r\n•    For smaller projects, the newer \"mix mobiles\" are popular. These  volumetric mixers, or mobile concrete plants on wheels, offer freshly  mixed concrete on demand. Contractors put in sand, coarse aggregate,  cement, water and other additives to the belts and bins to create fresh  concrete on-site. For smaller projects, customers can order more exact  amounts when using the volumetric mixers. Often when using drum mixers,  they must order extra concrete to ensure that they have enough for the  project. Contractors also save money because this method produces less  waste. Some contractors also buy specialized pumps for pumping ready-mix  concrete. If customers need a concrete pumped in, contractors who own  their own pumps are at a significant advantage. Contractors can also  contract out their pumping services to other concrete companies without a  pump.\r\nConsiderations\r\n•    For concrete equipment, preventative care is essential for good  use. It is necessary to pressure wash, check and adjust the equipment as  needed. Some contractors may buy used equipment because the costs of  mixers, pumps and other equipment is quite high. However, a breakdown in  equipment may irritate customers and cause a contractor to lose a  valuable contract. New equipment may be worth the cost for its  reliability factor and manufacturer\'s warranty.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.ehow.com/about_4572414_readymix-concrete-equipment.html#ixzz1LrAzqswT\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Batch Plant Mixer','','inherit','open','open','','46-revision-7','','','2011-06-13 19:53:02','2011-06-13 19:53:02','',46,'http://www.gulfatlanticequipment.com/blog/46-revision-7',0,'revision','',0),(184,1,'2011-06-06 18:43:06','2011-06-06 18:43:06','A batch plant mixer is usually used when it comes to using ready-mixed  concrete. This is because it saves a lot of time and is ideal with large  projects. It originated from the 1940s, when the world was trying to  build back after the war, and is still popular in many building projects  now. The batch plant mixer is perfect to be used in sm