t-size: x-small;\">The GreyStone Dewatering Screen is available in three different models—the <strong>DS-488</strong> (4-ft x 8-ft),<strong> DS-6010 </strong>(5-ft x 10-ft) and <strong>DS-7212 </strong>(6-ft  x 12-ft)—to efficiently dewater up to 300 TPH with no runoff or water  pools. While most concrete and masonry sands typically retain from 18 to  24 percent moisture, the GreyStone Dewatering Screen cuts that moisture  down to as low as 10 percent—providing salable material in less than a  day. It utilizes two vibrators that initiate a linear motion, driving  particles in an uphill, downhill or horizontal direction. A  high-frequency liquid/solids separator allows producers to easily adjust  bed depth, table tilt and vibrator variables to remove up to 50 percent  of the water, no matter how wet the material is. The urethane deck  dewaters a broad range of particle sizes and can preserve fines smaller  than 200 mesh.</span>\n\nThe Aggre-Dry® Fine Material Washer Screen  combines a fine material screw and  dewatering screen to produce sand and gravel products with a moisture  content as low as 8 to 13 percent, by weight, while using only 30 hp to  wash and dewater up to 100 TPH.\nHere’s how the energy- and  cost-efficient Aggre-Dry FMW Screen washes and dewaters aggregate  material: a standard GreyStone inclined single-spiral fine material  washer (FMW) initially dewaters the material, doing the bulk of the  work. At the same time, the rotation of the dewatering screw scrubs the  material to help remove surface dirt. The action of the screw flights  sends the sand up the inclined tub, and ensures that the dewatering  screen located at the top of the flights will be evenly fed. The  vibratory dewatering screen further removes moisture from the sand. This  combined process produces a caked, dry sand product that neither an  inclined dewatering screw nor a vibratory screen can separately achieve.\nThe  GreyStone dewatering screen, curved around the spiral flights on the  Aggre-Dry FMW Screen, has several unique features. A 0.25-mm screen  opening reduces the amount of material that can fall through the screen.  The feed from the screw allows the material to build to a bed depth of  14 inches on the screen, squeezing additional moisture from the sand as  the vibratory motors move it along the length of the screen cloth,  further reducing moisture content.\nIn its most innovative feature,  this GreyStone unit re-introduces the throughs from the screen back into  the screw’s washing process, where the screw portion of the unit again  pushes it to the unit’s dewatering screen, increasing the amount of  salable product. This process eliminates the need for costly pumps and  cyclone sand separation systems — along with the additional horsepower  this equipment requires. In fact, the Aggre-Dry FMW Screen should use  less than half of the horsepower required to process the same tonnage of  spec product on a traditional screen / cyclone system. In addition,  GreyStone has increased the water handling capacity of these units,  making the Aggre-Dry even more versatile for aggregate producers.\nAs  production of these units increases, GreyStone will offer them in all of  the company’s standard fine material washer sizes, from 36-inches x  28-feet to 84-inches x 38 feet.\nGreyStone manufactures a complete  line of field-proven portable and semi-portable washing/screening  plants, sand classification tanks and systems, single and twin fine  material dewatering screws, single and twin coarse material washers, log  washers, advanced computer control systems, portable sand plants, water  clarifiers, rotary and vibrating screens, portable conveyors and radial  stackers, blade mills, dewatering screens, portable screening plants,  twin jets, cutter heads and aggregate reclaiming systems.\n\n<strong>D</strong>ewatering screens allow producers to sell  material faster by eliminating waiting periods for stockpile drying.  Many concrete and masonry sands typically retain from 18 to 24 percent  moisture, which generally requires between one-to-two weeks of drying  time before it can be sold. At the end of your operation,  Dewatering Screens can receive a high percentage of water-saturated fine  material and produce a dense, compact cake that rides up the belt and  forms a pile with no runoff or water pools. The end result is a dry,  transportable product—with a moisture content as low as 8 percent—that  can be sold in less than a day.\n\nA number of models are available to handle a variety of  capacities to efficiently dewater up to 350  tons per hour. GreyStone’s Dewatering Screens are constructed of  high-quality ASTM A36 structural steel for years of trouble-free service  life.\n\n<strong>Features and Benefits of Dewatering Screens</strong>\n• Adapts to each plant’s unique material by combining the adjustable motor force in conjunction with the adjustable bed tilt. Once setup is achieved with favorable steady-state conditions, operation starts with a simple flip of a switch.\n• The sand stockpile produced stacks high and nearly dry, without forming water pools at the base of the equipment. Eliminating water runoff from material stockpiles helps producers answer local environmental concerns.\n• A high-frequency separator allows producers to easily adjust bed depth, table tilt and vibrator variables to remove up to 50 percent of the water, while maintaining maximum production no matter how wet the material is.\nTwo vibrators initiate a linear motion, driving particles in an uphill, downhill or horizontal direction—so water is strained down through the sand bed and below the screen deck.\n• A urethane deck with a 1/4-mm aperture allows the user to dewater a broad range of particle sizes. The deck can handle up to 14 inches of material depth, making use of the bottom thin layer of material as a secondary “screen,” allowing the deck to preserve fines smaller than 200 mesh.\n• A +/- 5-degree bed angle tilt allows producer to better adapt to material volume, gradation and water retention changes and create the proper material bed depth.\n\nWith high quality classifier configurations and the right equipment to  supply all your washing, classifying and dewatering equipment needs,  Gulf Atlantic Industrial Equipment, Inc. can custom-design a complete operation to meet your specific  application and production requirements. You can send them a sample of  your pit run material for a free sieve analysis and recommendation.','Greystone Dewatering Screen','','inherit','open','open','','167-revision-4','','','2011-06-06 21:45:08','2011-06-06 21:45:08','',167,'http://www.gulfatlanticequipment.com/blog/167-revision-4',0,'revision','',0),(195,1,'2011-06-06 21:46:46','2011-06-06 21:46:46','Roller-Compacted Concrete (RCC) or rolled concrete is a special blend of concrete that has the same ingredients as conventional concrete but in different ratios. It has cement, water, and aggregates, but RCC is much drier and essentially has no slump. RCC is placed in a manner similar to paving, often by dump trucks or conveyors, spread by bulldozers or special modified asphalt pavers. After placement it is compacted by vibratory rollers.\nRCC is typically used for concrete pavement, but it is increasingly used to build concrete dams because the low cement content causes less heat to be generated while curing than do conventional massive concrete pours.\nFor dam applications, RCC sections are built lift-by-lift in successive horizontal layers resulting in a downstream slope that resembles a concrete staircase. Once a layer is placed, it can immediately support the earth-moving equipment to place the next layer. After RCC is deposited on the lift surface, small dozers typically spread it in one-foot-thick layers (300mm).[2]\nRCC, a durable paving material that carries heavy loads, is now developing as a fast, economical construction method for dams, off-highway pavement projects, heavy-duty parking and storage areas, and as a base for conventional pavement. RCC is a stiff, zero-slump concrete mixture with the consistency of damp gravel comprised of local aggregates or crushed recycled concrete, Portland cement, and water. The mixture is placed and roller compacted with the same commonly available equipment used for asphalt pavement construction. The process requires no forms, finishing, surface texturing, or joint sawing and sealing.\nBecause of its low water-cement ratio, RCC typically has high strengths similar to, or even greater than, conventional concrete. RCC\'s high-strength properties combined with ease of construction and high rate of production often make RCC more economical than a flexible pavement. Additionally, more than 20 years of exposure as logging roads in cold climates have demonstrated that RCC has adequate resistance to freezing and thawing.\nRCC got its start in the Seventies, when the Canadian logging industry switched to environmentally cleaner, land-based log-sorting methods. The industry needed a strong pavement to stand up to massive loads and specialized equipment. Yet economy was equally important: log-sorting yards can span 40 acres or more. RCC met this challenge and has since expanded to other heavy-duty applications.\nToday, RCC is used when strength, durability, and economy are primary needs:\nPort, intermodal, and military facilities; parking, storage, and staging areas;\nstreets, intersections, and low-speed roads.\nRCC\'s economy of scale made it ideal for roads, parking, and staging areas at the Honda Plant in Lincoln, Alabama. At 140 acres, it\'s the largest RCC pavement project to date.\nRCC owes much of its economy to high-volume, high-speed construction methods. Large-capacity mixers set the pace. Normally, RCC is blended in continuous-mixing pugmills at or near the construction site. These high-output pugmills have the mixing efficiency needed to evenly disperse the relatively small amount of water used.\nDump trucks transport the RCC and discharge it into an asphalt paver, which places the material in layers up to 10 inches thick and 42 feet wide.\nNo rutting, no pot holes, the high strength of RCC pavements eliminates common and costly problems traditionally associated with asphalt pavements. RCC pavements not only resist rutting they span soft localized sub-grades, will not deform under heavy, concentrated loads, do not deteriorate from spills of fuels and hydraulic fluids and will not soften under high temperatures.','Roller Compacted Concrete','','inherit','open','open','','68-revision-4','','','2011-06-06 21:46:46','2011-06-06 21:46:46','',68,'http://www.gulfatlanticequipment.com/blog/68-revision-4',0,'revision','',0),(302,1,'2011-07-07 17:11:54','2011-07-07 17:11:54','&nbsp;\n\nRCC is short for Roller Compacted Concrete which is a blend of concrete  which is similar to the usual concrete but just has a different ratio of  ingredients used in it. The ingredients used include cement, water and  aggregates but RCC tends to be drier and more rigid in nature than the  normal concrete that you may find. It is generally very stiff by  temperament and hence requires to be completely mixed before it can be  discharged. An RCC Mixer has specifically been designed to do this and to  convert any dry batch plant into a central mix and RCC plant.\n<h1>Types of RCC Mixers</h1>\nThere are various different RCC mixers made by several companies but the  two important ones with some advanced features and benefits include the  following:\n<ul>\n	<li><strong>Rapid International Model 400C</strong> and <strong> </strong>Continuous Mixing Plants - available either volumetric or weighed processing.</li>\n	<li><strong>Sicoma Mao 6000 Twin Shaft mixer</strong> mounted on a stationary or portable concrete batch plant.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Some of the advanced features of an RCC mixer  include the following:</h2>\n•    Continuous Blending: Continuous blending is done of the materials  making use of variable drive feeders and metering of cementitious  materials to give them an aggregate flow. The materials are sealed by  the sand part of the mixture and the rest are all in layers.\n•    Weigh Bridge: Through this feature, the weight of the aggregates  are measured and adjusted by the computer. It also measures the accuracy  of speed so the aggregate blending is made possible.\n•    Twin-Shaft Mixers: These are known to be reliable and  productive at the same time. They provide the most even mixture in the  shortest possible time.\n\nIt has a Sicoma Mao 6000 Twin Shaft mixer which is an added value since  it allows the mixer to give a perfectly homogenous mix in a shorter  period of time with up to 15 % less usage of cement. Hence it is able to  do cost saving for the company.\n\nOther features include water proof  doors, standard alarm unit in case of some faulty shaft seal lubrication  and maintenance free dry shaft seals.\nRT 3000 RCC Mixer\nSome of the advantages of this particular type of RCC Mixer are:\n•    Less space required.\n•    Robust and durable.\n•    Thorough mix for all aggregates.\n•    It has two uprated and heavy duty gear boxes which keeps excessive load from being burdened on the shaft.\n•    Built to last for long.\n•    Increased production.\n\nRapid International USA Roller Compacted Concrete(RCC)/Continuous Mixing Plants or Pugmill  Plants have been designed and developed to be a cost effective method  for the high capacity production of Concrete or for any application  where a cement or binder needs to be mixed into a base material.\n<ul>\n	<li>RCC/Continuous Mixing Plants/Pugmills are suitable for many different applications:</li>\n	<li>Mixing roller compacted concrete (RCC) for pavement</li>\n	<li>Cement Treated base (CTB) or Cement Stabilized Base for Road Construction</li>\n	<li>Environmental soil contamination applications</li>\n	<li>Soil stabilization</li>\n	<li>Sludge Solidification for non-hazardous and hazardous waste</li>\n	<li>Mine back fill</li>\n	<li>Bentonite land fill sealing for lagoons and protective cell lining</li>\n	<li>Dam construction and many other applications...</li>\n</ul>\n<div></div>','RCC Mixers','','inherit','open','open','','59-revision-7','','','2011-07-07 17:11:54','2011-07-07 17:11:54','',59,'http://www.gulfatlanticequipment.com/blog/59-revision-7',0,'revision','',0),(269,1,'2011-06-13 19:50:02','2011-06-13 19:50:02','<strong>Ready mix plants</strong>, also referred to as a batching plant, for concrete allows builders to manufacture customized cement  and transport that mixture to the  construction site as and when required. The product is normally  transported from the ready mix plants using truck mounted  transit mixers. This enables customized concrete to be produced which is  required on the construction sites. The world’s first ready mix  concrete plant was set up in 1930s, but the actual boom in the industry  began in 1960s, and has never looked back since.\r\n<h1>Ready Mix Plants</h1>\r\n<img class=\"alignright size-full wp-image-110\" title=\"ready-mix-plant\" src=\"http://www.gulfatlanticequipment.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/ready-mix-plant.jpg\" alt=\"ready mix plants\" width=\"300\" height=\"160\" />\r\nThe main purpose of concrete <em>ready mix plants</em> is to provide  concrete to construction sites on a timely basis. When a batch of ready mix concrete  is required, the nearest plants are normally favored in order to  minimize transport time and cost. At the plant, raw materials are stored  in hoppers and silos and mixed using advanced computerized systems. The  ready mixed concrete plant is required to equip itself with up-to-date  equipments, such as transit mixer, concrete pump, and concrete batching  plant, which needs visualized production management software and also  PLC controller. Experienced batchers continuously monitor the processes  to ensure that the quality of cement meets the expectations of the client.\r\n\r\n<strong>HOW DO READY MIX PLANTS WORK WITH MATERIALS?</strong>\r\n•    Hydration: After raw materials, water, and cement are combined, the  mixture remains in a fluid state for about 5 hours, allowing  transportation, placements and finishing at the intended building site.  During hydration, cement crystals radiate and mesh with crystals of  water and other raw materials, resulting in stiffening and hardening of  cement. Once the cement is thoroughly mixed, it should be placed at the  required places before it sets.\r\n\r\n•    Proportioning: This involves proportioning of a <a style=\"text-decoration: none; color: black;\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Concrete\">concrete</a> mix  design to make it economical and enable it to achieve the properties  required for its intended use. The experts at the ready mixed concrete  plant can select the material proportions for the performance you  require, or you may specify your requirements yourself through job  specifications.\r\n<h2><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">READY MIX PLANTS</span></h2>\r\n<strong>Types</strong>\r\n\r\nThere are four different types of ready mix concrete.\r\n•    <strong>Truck Mixed Concrete:</strong> In this method, all the raw ingredients are  mixed during the transit. Most of the water is batched at the plant and  the mixer drum is turned at fast speeds during loading of the materials.  The mixing can be done either at the job site, in the plant itself  before dispatch, or during the transit period itself.\r\n\r\n•   <strong> Shrink Mixed Concrete:</strong> This method involves initial mixing in  the plant mixer after which the concrete is loaded into the truck mixer  to be mixed completely during the transit. The amount and time of mixing  done in the truck mixer is determined using mixer uniformity tests.\r\n\r\n•   <strong> Central Mixed Concrete:</strong> The entire mixing process is completed in  the plant mixer and the cement is loaded onto the truck mixer for  transport. In this method, the truck mixer is used mainly as a  transporter of the ready mix concrete.\r\n<h3>Ready Mix Plants</h3>\r\nUsing ready mix concrete at your construction site could be an excellent  decision which would result in higher efficiency and time savings along  with reduced costs. Also, every load of concrete you use will be fresh  as it has been mixed either on the way to the construction site or at  the construction site itself. Moreover, large construction assignments  such as road paving can depend on a consistent quality of cement in  every truckload. Another aspect where costs are reduced is that labor  at the construction site earlier used for cement production can be  assigned other jobs, and there is also reduced requirement for storage  space at the site.\r\n\r\n<strong>Related Articles:</strong>\r\n\r\n<address>For more information on purchasing <a href=\"http://www.gulfatlanticequipment.com\" target=\"_blank\">concrete batch plants </a>\r\n</address> <address>More information on <a title=\"portable concrete plants\" href=\"http://www.gulfatlanticequipment.com/blog/portable-concrete-plants\">portable concrete plants</a></address> <address>More information on <a href=\"http://http://www.gulfatlanticequipment.com/blog/mobile-batch-plant\">mobile match plant</a></address> <address> </address> <address>More information on <a href=\"http://www.gulfatlanticequipment.com\">ready mix plants</a></address> <address> </address> <address> </address>\r\n<div id=\"suggestions\"></div>','Ready Mix Plants','','inherit','open','open','','62-revision-30','','','2011-06-13 19:50:02','2011-06-13 19:50:02','',62,'http://www.gulfatlanticequipment.com/blog/62-revision-30',0,'revision','',0),(268,1,'2011-06-21 16:47:56','2011-06-21 16:47:56','RCC is short for Roller Compacted Concrete which is a blend of concrete  which is similar to the usual concrete but just has a different ratio of  ingredients used in it. The ingredients used include cement, water and  aggregates but RCC tends to be drier an