c yards.\n\nBy using a batch plant mixer, the means that the concrete will then  need to be moved to a truck mixer to be able to deliver the product to the job site.\n\n•    Ready-mix concrete can be mixed in a variety of ways. Concrete  can be mixed with the truck mixers, and this type of concrete is called  truck-mixed, or transit-mixed, concrete.  Ready-mix concrete can also be  mixed in a plant mixer, then moved to the drum of the truck mixer.  These central mixing plants use a stationary mixer to partially mix the  concrete. This type of concrete is called shrink-mixed concrete, since  it reduces the volume of the concrete. The final type of concrete mixing  used is called central mixing, or wet batch, concrete. Central mixing  is cost-effective since it requires less wear on the truck drums.  However, some plant mixers may require more maintenance, but they  produce higher quality concrete due to the superior mixing.\n\nFunction\n•    Ready-mix concrete is usually delivered by trucks with rotating  drum mixers. Drum mixer trucks are designed with a pair of blades that  spin one way to mix the concrete, and then can spin the opposite  direction to release the mixture. Although most concrete mixer trucks  discharge concrete from the back, newer trucks feature front-discharge  chutes. These front-discharge trucks require less maneuvering to place  the concrete in the correct location.\nTypes\n•    Types of plant mixers include: tilt drum mixer, horizontal shaft  mixers, pan mixers and slurry mixers. Tilt drum mixers are the most  common and are known for their efficiency. Horizontal shaft mixers are  good for producing higher-quality concrete products because of their  powerful blending capabilities.  Pan mixers are used for pre-cast concrete operations.\nBenefits\n•    For smaller projects, the newer \"mix mobiles\" are popular. These  volumetric mixers, or mobile concrete plants on wheels, offer freshly  mixed concrete on demand. Contractors put in sand, coarse aggregate,  cement, water and other additives to the belts and bins to create fresh  concrete on-site. For smaller projects, customers can order more exact  amounts when using the volumetric mixers. Often when using drum mixers,  they must order extra concrete to ensure that they have enough for the  project. Contractors also save money because this method produces less  waste. Some contractors also buy specialized pumps for pumping ready-mix  concrete. If customers need a concrete pumped in, contractors who own  their own pumps are at a significant advantage. Contractors can also  contract out their pumping services to other concrete companies without a  pump.\nConsiderations\n•    For concrete equipment, preventative care is essential for good  use. It is necessary to pressure wash, check and adjust the equipment as  needed. Some contractors may buy used equipment because the costs of  mixers, pumps and other equipment is quite high. However, a breakdown in  equipment may irritate customers and cause a contractor to lose a  valuable contract. New equipment may be worth the cost for its  reliability factor and manufacturer\'s warranty.\n\nRead more: About Ready-Mix Concrete Equipment | eHow.com  http://www.ehow.com/about_4572414_readymix-concrete-equipment.html#ixzz1LrAzqswT','Batch Plant Mixer','','inherit','open','open','','46-revision-5','','','2011-06-13 19:52:07','2011-06-13 19:52:07','',46,'http://www.gulfatlanticequipment.com/blog/46-revision-5',0,'revision','',0),(228,1,'2011-06-13 19:49:35','2011-06-13 19:49:35','<strong>Ready mix plants</strong>, also referred to as a batching plant, for concrete allows builders to manufacture customized cement  and transport that mixture to the  construction site as and when required. The product is normally  transported from the ready mix plants using truck mounted  transit mixers. This enables customized concrete to be produced which is  required on the construction sites. The world’s first ready mix  concrete plant was set up in 1930s, but the actual boom in the industry  began in 1960s, and has never looked back since.\n<h1>Ready Mix Plants</h1>\n<img class=\"alignright size-full wp-image-110\" title=\"ready-mix-plant\" src=\"http://www.gulfatlanticequipment.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/ready-mix-plant.jpg\" alt=\"ready mix plants\" width=\"300\" height=\"160\" />\nThe main purpose of concrete <em>ready mix plants</em> is to provide  concrete to construction sites on a timely basis. When a batch of ready mix concrete  is required, the nearest plants are normally favored in order to  minimize transport time and cost. At the plant, raw materials are stored  in hoppers and silos and mixed using advanced computerized systems. The  ready mixed concrete plant is required to equip itself with up-to-date  equipments, such as transit mixer, concrete pump, and concrete batching  plant, which needs visualized production management software and also  PLC controller. Experienced batchers continuously monitor the processes  to ensure that the quality of cement meets the expectations of the client.\n\n<strong>HOW DO READY MIX PLANTS WORK WITH MATERIALS?</strong>\n•    Hydration: After raw materials, water, and cement are combined, the  mixture remains in a fluid state for about 5 hours, allowing  transportation, placements and finishing at the intended building site.  During hydration, cement crystals radiate and mesh with crystals of  water and other raw materials, resulting in stiffening and hardening of  cement. Once the cement is thoroughly mixed, it should be placed at the  required places before it sets.\n\n•    Proportioning: This involves proportioning of a <a style=\"text-decoration: none; color: black;\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Concrete\">concrete</a> mix  design to make it economical and enable it to achieve the properties  required for its intended use. The experts at the ready mixed concrete  plant can select the material proportions for the performance you  require, or you may specify your requirements yourself through job  specifications.\n<h2><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">READY MIX PLANTS</span></h2>\n<strong>Types</strong>\n\nThere are four different types of ready mix concrete.\n•    <strong>Truck Mixed Concrete:</strong> In this method, all the raw ingredients are  mixed during the transit. Most of the water is batched at the plant and  the mixer drum is turned at fast speeds during loading of the materials.  The mixing can be done either at the job site, in the plant itself  before dispatch, or during the transit period itself.\n\n•   <strong> Shrink Mixed Concrete:</strong> This method involves initial mixing in  the plant mixer after which the concrete is loaded into the truck mixer  to be mixed completely during the transit. The amount and time of mixing  done in the truck mixer is determined using mixer uniformity tests.\n\n•   <strong> Central Mixed Concrete:</strong> The entire mixing process is completed in  the plant mixer and the cement is loaded onto the truck mixer for  transport. In this method, the truck mixer is used mainly as a  transporter of the ready mix concrete.\n<h3>Ready Mix Plants</h3>\nUsing ready mix concrete at your construction site could be an excellent  decision which would result in higher efficiency and time savings along  with reduced costs. Also, every load of concrete you use will be fresh  as it has been mixed either on the way to the construction site or at  the construction site itself. Moreover, large construction assignments  such as road paving can depend on a consistent quality of cement in  every truckload. Another aspect where costs are reduced is that labor  at the construction site earlier used for cement production can be  assigned other jobs, and there is also reduced requirement for storage  space at the site.\n\n<strong>Related Articles:</strong>\n\n<address>For more information on purchasing <a href=\"http://www.gulfatlanticequipment.com\" target=\"_b